SIMPLE: infinity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infinity
<hw>In*fin"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Infinities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>infinitas</ets>;
pref. <ets>in-</ets> not + <ets>finis</ets> boundary, limit, end: cf. F.
<ets>infinit⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See <er>Finite</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Unlimited extent of time, space, or quantity;
eternity; boundlessness; immensity.</def> <rj><au>Sir T.
More.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There can not be more <qex>infinities</qex> than one; for one of
them would limit the other.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj> <--
now known to be false! -- See aleph null, etc.-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unlimited capacity, energy, excellence, or
knowledge; <as>as, the <ex>infinity</ex> of God and his
perfections</as>.</def> <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Endless or indefinite number; great multitude; as an
<xex>infinity</xex> of beauties.</def> <rj><au>Broome.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 760 --></p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A quantity greater than any
assignable quantity of the same kind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Mathematically considered, infinity is always a limit of
a variable quantity, resulting from a particular supposition made upon
the varying element which enters it.</note> <rj><au>Davies & Peck (Math.
Dict.).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>That part of a line, or of a
plane, or of space, which is infinitely distant. In modern geometry,
parallel lines or planes are sometimes treated as lines or planes
meeting at infinity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Circle at infinity</b></col>, <cd>an imaginary circle at
infinity, through which, in geometry of three dimensions, every sphere
is imagined to pass.</cd> -- <col><b>Circular points at
infinity</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Circular</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infirm</ent>⟦br⟧
